The meeting took place on Monday, September 22, 2025, and everyone in the team participated through Discord.  We used Google Docs to collect ideas and ranked ideas based on our individual preferences that align with most of us.

**Whole team:**

* Kind of settled on a water monitoring system  
* Detection would probably be simpler compared to doing work on the water

**K’s ideas: Active sensor vs. passive sensor**

* Active: Constantly providing readings  
* Passive: Lets you know when it has detected something

**Neel’s ideas: Water quality sensor that senses conductance and pH**

* One subsystem would be control  
* pH monitoring system  
* Conductance monitoring system  
  * Could use a battery to see if current flows, which would prove conductivity  
* Clarity measuring system  
* Believes software will need to be incorporated for one of the subsystems  
* A system that lets the user know something is bad  
  * Could be buzzers, lights, or some other warning  
* User interface  
  * Might have a screen, some dials or buttons  
* Optical sensor  
* A sterilization system that can clean water  
  * Supposedly simple

**Jacob’s ideas: Air something**

* Something that measures Ar-41 to see if the air has become contaminated  
* Salinity cells are used to actively measure the conductivity of water  
* A filter is included with a flow meter to measure something like total dissolved solids or large particulate matter

**Asadbek’s ideas:** 

* Water quality sensor  
  * pH monitor  
* Gas sensor  
* Including buzzer and LCD monitor

| Requirement/Need | Feature | Details |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Water quality monitoring | [PH0-14 sensor](https://a.co/d/952ob1d) | To check if the water is of good quality and safe to drink |
| Hazardous gas detection | [Mq 135](https://a.co/d/2AQBerO) | Helps to know if gas leaks or benzene vapor, sulfur detection, or if someone smokes around, so ASU can sue them for smoking on campus because some people have allergies and those people are 2nd hand smoke |
| Showcasing results | LCD monitor | Will show updates on monitoring |
| Buzzer | Buzzer | It will buzz and tell people around to be safe |

| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **Excellent (5 points)** | Separate warning systems for different sensors | ‘Guide’ mode, which displays general guidelines for acceptable levels of water pH and clarity | The device quickly measures all qualities advertised | Easy-to-understand data |
| **Above average (4 points)** | Vibrating device | Simple navigation buttons | Measures pH levels | Easy to use |
| **Average (3 points)** | Buzzer | LCD screen | Measures Total Dissolved Solids | Easy to calibrate |
| **Below average (2 points)** | LED lights | Adjustable font size | Measures conductivity | Ergonomic design |
| **Needs work (1 point)** | The screen displays a warning | Backlight to make the screen brighter | Measures optical clarity | No sharp corners for kid-friendly design |

Concept 1: A self-contained portable unit with buttons for navigation, a screen, and warning lights. Water is sampled from a single port.

Concept 2: A mult-functional sensor/probe unit containing conductivity and pH sensors through two electrodes and a water clarity sensor through an optic aimed at a target.

Concept 3: A benchtop-style device where water can be poured in through the input and analyzed from the output of the screen.
